  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged from efforts to combat organized crime in the 1920s-1930s\n- Initially focused on disrupting criminal financial flows\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970):\n- First comprehensive U.S. legislation targeting financial crime\n- Required banks to report large cash transactions\n- Created framework for tracking suspicious financial activities\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as global problem\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating financial crimes\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Anti-Drug Abuse Act (1988)\n- RICO statutes\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n\n5. Key Expansion Areas:\n- Terrorism financing prevention\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- Expanded reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n6. Modern Trends:\n- Increasingly complex regulatory frameworks\n- Advanced technological tracking methods\n- Greater cross-border collaboration in enforcement\n\nThe legal landscape continues evolving to address emerging financial crime techniques.",
